According to Goetz:
&gt; In order to use client-side locking, you must know what lock X uses

`ConcurrentHashMap` doesn&#39;t use lock on `this` internally, instead it uses sophisticated locking mechanism, which is called Lock Stripping (locking occurs on several buckets or stripes, meaning that accessing a bucket only locks that bucket and not the entire data structure).

Moreover, the documentation of a class that supports client-side locking should explicitly state its applicability. `ConcurrentHashMap` should not be used for client-side locking because its documentation states that:
&gt; even though all operations are thread-safe, **retrieval operations do
&gt; not entail locking**, and there is not any support for locking the
&gt; entire table in a way that prevents **all** access. This class is fully
&gt; interoperable with Hashtable in programs that rely on its thread
&gt; safety but not on its synchronization details.


For instance, `ConcurrentHashMap#get` and `ConcurrentHashMap#put`  methods are not synchronized methods so if you lock `ConcurrentHashMap` object for &quot;exclusive access&quot; inside `Service1`, another Thread can enter `ConcurrentHashMap#put` method from `Service2` and modify internal state of `ConcurrentHashMap` object (which wouldn&#39;t happen with `Collections.synchronizedMap(..)` or `Hashtable` because all their methods are synchronized and would be locked in this case):

     ConcurrentHashMap map = new ConcurrentHashMap(); // will be passed into Service1 and Service2
     map.put(&quot;key&quot;, &quot;not sold&quot;); // initial value


.

    public class Service1 {
    
        public void method1(ConcurrentHashMap map) { // raw use of parametrized class for brevity
            synchronized(map) { // Thread1: lock for &quot;exclusive access&quot;
                map.get(&quot;key&quot;); // Thread1: expecting to get &quot;not sold&quot; initial value
            }
        }
    }

.

    public class Service2 {
    
        public void method2(ConcurrentHashMap map) { // raw use of parametrized class for brevity
            // somebody forgot to lock for exclusive access
            map.put(&quot;key&quot;, &quot;sold&quot;); // Thread2: nothing prevents Thread2 from modifying map while Service1 gaining exclusive access because ConcurrentHashMap#put is not synchronized
        }
    }

    ConcurrentHashMap&lt;AType&gt; concurrentMap = new ConcurrentHashMap&lt;AType&gt;();
    
    synchronized(concurrentMap){
      //do something
    }

The above code do not work because of the fact that the lock[more than one lock to be correct(default is 16)] used by the concurrent map is not the concurrent object itself. Concurrent objects are designed to be scalable. 

Java memory model guarantees works on the notion of &#39;happens before&#39;.
If a lock acquired by a thread and released after, the thread which then acquires the lock sees everything earlier thread sees when it released the lock. However, this relationship only works if the same lock is used.

The above code acquire the lock associated with the concurrent map object. This is like acquiring a lock associated with any other object. However, the lock is not the same one used in the implementation of concurrent map.

