```lang-none
2018-05-12T20:30:00Z
```

Note that I [prefer u to y](https://stackoverflow.com/a/65928023/10819573) with `DateTimeFormatter`.

An alternative solution using the modern date-time API
--

You can convert the obtained `LocalDateTime` directly into an `Instant` using [`LocalDateTime#toInstant`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/chrono/ChronoLocalDateTime.html#toInstant-java.time.ZoneOffset-) by supplying it with the time-zone ID.

